1585","1596":"1596","1549":"1549","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1522–":"1522–Deceased","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1522–Female":"1522–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1522":"1522","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1549":"1549","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Scottish:  see  Woodburn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodburn","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Woodburn in Corsenside (Northumberland), Woodburn (Ayrshire, Kincardineshire, Midlothian), or Woodburn in Oakford (Devon). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’, i.e. a stream flowing through a wood."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":27,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":36,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":47,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":63,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705208,"age":65,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":98,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Margaret Woodborne was born in 1522, in England. She married John WOODBORNE in 1535, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1522–":"1522–Surnud","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1522–Female":"1522–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1522":"1522","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1549":"1549","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1522–":"1522–Kuollut","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1522–Female":"1522–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1522":"1522","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1549":"1549","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1522–":"1522–Décédée","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1522–Female":"1522–Décédée","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1522":"1522","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1549":"1549","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Margaret Woodborne est née en 1522, à Angleterre. Elle a épousé John WOODBORNE en 1535, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1522–":"1522–Verstorben","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1535–1596":"1535–1596","1522–Female":"1522–Verstorben","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1522":"1522","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1575":"1575","1520":"1520","1585":"1585","1596":"1596","1549":"1549","Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cottenham, Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Margaret Woodborne wurde 1522 in England geboren. Sie hat 1535 in England John WOODBORNE geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1522–":"1522–Desede","1520–1575":"1520–1575","1